steve-b@access.digex.net (Steve Brinich) writes:

>   The usual implementations of public-key cryptography (RIPEM, PGP, etc)
> encrypt each file via a randomly-generated session key, and then encrypt
> the session key via the user's secret key.
                          ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^

How can that be?  Wouldn't that mean that anyone can obtain the
session key by decrypting it using the user's public key?

I thought that PGP encrypts the randomly-generated session key using
the recipient's public key, so that only the recipient can feed the
session key to IDEA to decrypt the body of the message.
